nib.text:
Mayor Mike Elliot has issued a city-wide curfew lasting from 11 p.m. through 6 a.m.

**The curfew does not apply to:** 
* Those traveling to and from work or religious services
* Those seeking medical care
* Those experiencing homelessness
* Members of the media 
* Emergency responders including law enforcement and medical services. 

Violation of the curfew is can result in a fine of $50.

Read the full text [here.](https://pbs.twimg.com/media/EzNrfElVEAwXxvz.jpg)

nib.text:
In a stark contrast to the relative peace of the night before, police made nearly 100 arrests at a demonstration outside of the Brooklyn Center Police Department Friday night.

Crowds gathered outside the Brooklyn Center Police Department for the fifth consecutive night Friday as demonstrators called for justice in the shooting of Daunte Wright.

Activists projected a “Justice 4 Daunte” sign across the street from police headquarters which remained fenced off with multiple law enforcement agencies standing by nearby.

In a midnight press conference, law enforcement officials said that they made nearly 100 arrests and displayed a range of objects that they say demonstrators threw at officers, including rocks and cans of beans. 

Police say that demonstrators were trying to cut the fence protecting the police department. 

On Thursday night, police reported no arrests at the demonstrations.
